Part II - Loan Data from Prosper Insights¶

by Agustin Barto¶

Investigation Overview¶

The purpose of the investigation was to look for the key influences on the loan rates and APR. While exploring the variables in isolation looking for potential candidates of these influences, we made several interesting discoveries. Here's a summary of what we discovered:

  • There was a dip in number of loans on 2009
  • Most loans are taken at the end of the year
  • BorrowerRate, BorrowerAPR and LenderYield have similar multi-modal distributions
  • Most loans are taken for debt consolidation
  • The vast majority of loans have 36 month terms
  • Half the borrowers are home owners
  • Loans are taken mostly on "round" amounts
  • BorrowerRage and BorrowerRate are highly correlated, but there's another variable that's grouping the loans
  • Higher credit grades (for both variables) lead to lower borrower rates
  • At least for deals after 2009, the term is a factor that increases the APR over the rate

Dataset Overview¶

The dataset contains loan information from Prosper from November 2005 until March 2015. It contains 113937 rows and 81 columns, both numerical and categorical describing differnt aspects of the loans.

Visualization 1¶

The following charts show that there was a dip in the number of loans taken in 2009. This can be explained by multiple factors (including the 2008 crash), but the dataset also seems to be "split" in 2009. Multiple variables have different distributions before and after 2009. We also need to ignore the first and last years as they're both partial.

Visualization 2¶

Most deals are taken near the end of the year. Given that most deals are taken for debt consolidation, there must a financial reason for this behavior.

Visualization 3¶

BorrowerRate, BorrowerAPR and LenderYield have similar multi-modal distributions. This is not surprising as the APR is the rate plus fees, and the yield is a function of the rate.

Visualization 4¶

Most loans are taken for debt consolidation. This is quite a common financial practice where a debtor takes a loan to repay other existing loans.

Visualization 5¶

For loans taken AFTER 2009, the vast majority of loans have 36 month terms. For loans prior to 2009 we only see deals for 36 months.

Visualization 6¶

Half the borrowers are home owners.

Visualization 7¶

If we analyze the loan amount distribution, we'll notice several spikes at "round" values. Without these values, the loan amount has a right-skewed distribution.

Visualization 8¶

BorrowerAPR and BorrowerRate are highly correlated, but there's another variable (most likely categorical) that's grouping the loans after 2009.

Visualization 9¶

Higher credit grades (for both variables) lead to lower borrower rates.

Visualization 10¶

At least for deals after 2009, the term is a factor that increases the APR over the rate.
